```suggestion
instance isEmpty_leftMoves_mul (x y : PGame.{u})
    [IsEmpty (x.LeftMoves Ã— y.RightMoves âŠ• x.RightMoves Ã— y.LeftMoves] :
    IsEmpty (x * y).LeftMoves := â€¹_â€º
```
seems more principled (and avoids the instance duplication, and forgetting some combinations of instances as you have done now)
The combinations I omitted correspond to when either game is identical to the zero game. So actually, your approach should generalize those instances too.
Yes, that is indeed my point
Can you turn it around and make it simp?

This is an equivalence, not an equality. As for the subsequent result written for quotients, I'd argue that it should either stay in its current direction or not be a `simp` lemma at all. The intention of these theorems is to turn the more complex operations on games into comparatively well-characterized operations on ordinals.
Actually, I think it makes sense to simply remove the `simp` lemma. Even if the RHS is simpler to work with, it's not structurally simpler in the way `simp` is supposed to be.

> The intention of these theorems is to turn the more complex operations on games into comparatively well-characterized operations on ordinals.

Yes, but it is also a distributivity lemma, and distributivity lemmas are always written in the form "non-distributed = distributed" while yours is the other way around
I'll rewrite the lemmas, but keep the simps out then.
I don't understand this change. The statement is the same as before, right?
Since this is now in a separate code section, the infix notation is no longer there. I didn't think it was worth it to enable it for two statements.

```suggestion
alias âŸ¨game_eq, _âŸ© := equiv_iff_game_eq
```
Do you even need the `cases x; cases y`?
Yes, for whatever reason statements like `(mk xl xr xL xR + mk yl yr yL yR).LeftMoves = xl âŠ• yl` are def-eq, while `(x + y).LeftMoves = x.LeftMoves âŠ• y.LeftMoves` aren't.
That's quite weird. Eta for structures should have fixed this... unless it's something to do with well-founded recursion being irreducible by default now? I am confused

```suggestion
theorem toPGame_nadd (a b : Ordinal.{u}) : (a â™¯ b).toPGame â‰ˆ a.toPGame + b.toPGame := by
```

```suggestion
theorem toPGame_nadd_mk' (a b : Ordinal) : (âŸ¦(a â™¯ b).toPGameâŸ§ : Game) = âŸ¦a.toPGameâŸ§ + âŸ¦b.toPGameâŸ§ :=
```

```suggestion
theorem toPGame_nmul (a b : Ordinal.{u}) (a â¨³ b).toPGame â‰ˆ a.toPGame * b.toPGame := by
```
Putting `a` and `b` before the colon doesn't work, since it breaks the `termination_by` syntax.
Ugh, annoying. @nomeata? ðŸ˜‡
Stuff before the colon is in scope for `termination_by`, so just don't bind it there again?
Oh, I get the syntax now.

```suggestion
theorem toPGame_nmul_mk' (a b : Ordinal) : (âŸ¦(a â¨³ b).toPGameâŸ§ : Game) = âŸ¦a.toPGame * b.toPGameâŸ§ :=
```

```suggestion
/-- Natural multiplication of ordinals corresponds to the product of ordinals as games. -/
```
since we turned the lemma around. Same above

I feel like this lemma would make more sense as
```suggestion
theorem toPGame_nmul_mk' (a b : Ordinal) : (âŸ¦(a â¨³ b).toPGameâŸ§ : Game) = âŸ¦a.toPGameâŸ§ * âŸ¦b.toPGameâŸ§ :=
```
Don't we have a name for the map `Ordinal â†’ Game` given by `x â†¦ âŸ¦x.toPGameâŸ§`? If not, maybe it's worth giving it a name (probably `Ordinal.toGame`), even if it's just an `abbrev`.

Be careful! Multiplication isn't defined on games, as products of equivalent pre-games aren't always equivalent.

We don't have a name for that map yet. What's the notation for defining an abbreviation like that?

Ah! Yeah that's annoying. Then my suggestion doesn't really make sense.

The notation is `abbrev Ordinal.toGame (o : Ordinal) : Game := âŸ¦o.toPGameâŸ§` or `@[reducible, inline] def Ordinal.toGame (o : Ordinal) : Game := âŸ¦o.toPGameâŸ§`

```suggestion
theorem toGame_nadd (a b : Ordinal) : (a â™¯ b).toGame = a.toGame + b.toGame :=
```
You'll need a docstring

```suggestion
theorem toGame_nadd (a b : Ordinal) : (a â™¯ b).toGame = a.toGame + b.toGame :=
```

```suggestion
/-- The natural multiplication of ordinals corresponds to their product as pre-games. -/
```
